Title: Sparse Serial Tests of Uniformity for Random Number Generators  
Author: Pierre L'Ecuyer, Richard Simard and Stefan Wegenkittl 
Keyword: Random number generation, goodness-of-fit, serial test, collision test, m-tuple test, multinomial distribution, OPSO.  
Address: Montreal, C.P. 6128, Succ. Centre-Ville Montreal, H3C 3J7, Canada  Hellbrunnerstrasse 34, A-5020 Salzburg, Austria  
Affiliation: Departement d'Informatique et de Recherche Operationnelle Universite de  Institute of Mathematics, University of Salzburg  
Note: Version:  
Email: e-mail: lecuyer@iro.umontreal.ca  e-mail: ste@random.mat.sbg.ac.at  
Date: November 5, 1998  
Abstract: Different versions of the serial test for testing the uniformity and independence of vectors of successive values produced by a (pseudo)random number generator are studied. These tests partition the t-dimensional unit hypercube into k cubic cells of equal volume, generate n points (vectors) in this hypercube, count how many points fall in each cell, and compute a test statistic defined as the sum of values of some univariate function f applied to these k individual counters. Both the overlapping and the non-overlapping vectors are considered. For different families of generators, such as the linear congruential, Tausworthe, nonlinear inversive, etc., different ways of choosing these functions and of choosing k are compared, and formulas are obtained for the (estimated) sample size required to reject the null hypothesis of i.i.d. uniformity as a function of the period length of the generator. For the classes of alternatives that correspond to linear generators, the most efficient tests turn out to have k AE n (in contrast to what is usually done or recommended in simulation books) and use overlapping. 
